# Lock ordering and critical sections

When editing code that holds a mutex (`shared_lock`, `unique_lock`, or raw lock guard), follow these rules to avoid contention and deadlock.

## No I/O or heavy work under lock

**Do not** perform I/O or heavy computation while holding any lock:

- No file system, network, or blocking I/O: no `stat()`, `GetFileAttributes`, `ReadFile`, etc.
- No heavy computation — only in-memory reads/writes, simple condition checks, and short bookkeeping.

**Rationale:** Holding a lock across I/O blocks other threads and can cause latency spikes or deadlock. FileIndex uses a single `shared_mutex`; long-held locks serialize all readers and block writers.

## Lock ordering

**Never acquire more than one of these mutexes at a time** in the same thread (unless explicitly documented):

- **FileIndex** (`index_mutex_`)
- **SearchThreadPool** (`mutex_`)
- **UsnMonitor** (`mutex_`)
- **UsnJournalQueue** (`mutex_`)

Do not take SearchThreadPool’s or UsnMonitor’s mutex while holding FileIndex’s mutex. I/O and handle close (e.g. in UsnMonitor) must happen **outside** the lock.

## Pattern

- **3-phase when I/O is needed:** read path (or minimal data) under shared/unique lock → release lock → do I/O → re-acquire lock and update (e.g. LazyAttributeLoader, UpdateSize).
- Add a brief comment when non-obvious (e.g. “No I/O under this lock”) and link to project design docs if they exist.

**Reference:** AGENTS.md; add design docs under `docs/design/` when this repo documents lock ordering and I/O (USN_Windows pattern).
